00:00:00,540 --> 00:00:04,430
The reason why we asked you the last question about creating an error and

2
00:00:04,430 --> 00:00:08,570
fixing the error is because an important skill of developers

3
00:00:08,570 --> 00:00:11,330
is to be able to get past errors.

4
00:00:11,330 --> 00:00:14,255
There's no developer who writes code perfectly the first time.

5
00:00:14,255 --> 00:00:15,875
If you think about it,

6
00:00:15,875 --> 00:00:20,765
the whole Google search product was not written in one day perfectly.

7
00:00:20,765 --> 00:00:25,765
It was a lot of iteration over many years, and it continues to be.

8
00:00:25,765 --> 00:00:30,203
So, regardless of whether you're a new developer or you're an experienced

9
00:00:30,203 --> 00:00:34,794
developer, in order to get to the end goal, it's not exactly a straight path.

10
00:00:34,794 --> 00:00:39,087
You'll run into obstacles along the way, and you have to be really creative in

11
00:00:39,087 --> 00:00:43,650
terms of trying to come up with other solutions to go around that obstacle.

12
00:00:43,650 --> 00:00:47,880
So once you get around it, then you'll run into another obstacle and so on.

13
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:50,860
And you just always want to keep thinking of ways to get

14
00:00:50,860 --> 00:00:52,640
around that obstacle.

15
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:59,680
And eventually, after a lot of work, you finally find the path to the goal, and

16
00:00:59,680 --> 00:01:03,400
even though it was super challenging, it was totally worth it in the end because

17
00:01:03,400 --> 00:01:08,060
you feel empowered and confident and just really proud of your work.

18
00:01:08,060 --> 00:01:11,700
So the really good developers know how to rebound from an error and

19
00:01:11,700 --> 00:01:13,220
continue with their work.

20
00:01:13,220 --> 00:01:14,330
So here are some habits and

21
00:01:14,330 --> 00:01:19,810
strategies that they use to debug, or fix, their errors.

22
00:01:19,810 --> 00:01:21,920
First they read the error message.

23
00:01:21,920 --> 00:01:24,770
When you're writing a document in Google Docs, for example,

24
00:01:24,770 --> 00:01:29,280
if there's any misspellings, then it will tell you with a red underline.

25
00:01:29,280 --> 00:01:34,250
Similarly in Android Studio, if you have typed XML incorrectly, then

26
00:01:34,250 --> 00:01:38,810
it will have a red, squiggly underline, or it will be highlighted in red.

27
00:01:38,810 --> 00:01:40,866
Also, in this bar on the side here,

28
00:01:40,866 --> 00:01:44,169
it will show you the message if you hover over the red bar.

29
00:01:44,169 --> 00:01:48,871
But in our XML Visualizer, there's also helpful error messages.

30
00:01:48,871 --> 00:01:52,996
So if I create an error, like removing this quotation mark, it will tell me

31
00:01:52,996 --> 00:01:57,350
that there's an uneven number of quotes and that I need to fix it.

32
00:01:57,350 --> 00:02:00,630
Sometimes, it also tells you the line number that the problem is on.

33
00:02:00,630 --> 00:02:03,320
The line numbers are on the left hand side here.

34
00:02:03,320 --> 00:02:06,320
So, on line six, we know that there's a problem.

35
00:02:06,320 --> 00:02:10,370
This helps narrow down the problem space instead of having to read through all

36
00:02:10,370 --> 00:02:13,210
your code and trying to figure out what the problem is.

37
00:02:13,210 --> 00:02:15,720
If you still don't understand the error message, try to

38
00:02:15,720 --> 00:02:19,780
identify words that you do understand and the words that you don't understand.

39
00:02:19,780 --> 00:02:24,170
You can always Google search for the words that you don't understand, or you

40
00:02:24,170 --> 00:02:28,440
can just copy the whole error message and paste that into a Google search.

41
00:02:28,440 --> 00:02:31,150
The other technique is to use working code samples and

42
00:02:31,150 --> 00:02:34,970
compare it to what you have to try to figure out what went wrong.

43
00:02:34,970 --> 00:02:38,310
We've already given you some code to look at in the last few videos, and

44
